ransient-mapping-sparrow\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"Stop\",\"hookName\":\"Stop\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code stop\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"a9aeba52-7d78-48fe-bb08-fbd074a5e606\",\"toolUseID\":\"a9aeba52-7d78-48fe-bb08-fbd074a5e606\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-19T16:20:50.809Z\",\"uuid\":\"9936917d-6f32-43b8-97ad-a37c84dd3008\"}\n{\"type\":\"queue-operation\",\"operation\":\"dequeue\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-19T16:20:51.128Z\",\"sessionId\":\"be7201dc-0742-46dc-83f7-b77432d86dbe\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"9936917d-6f32-43b8-97ad-a37c84dd3008\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"be7201dc-0742-46dc-83f7-b77432d86dbe\",\"version\":\"2.1.47\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"transient-mapping-sparrow\",\"type\":\"system\",\"subtype\":\"stop_hook_summary\",\"hookCount\":1,\"hookInfos\":[{\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code stop\"}],\"hookErrors\":[],\"preventedContinuation\":false,\"stopReason\":\"\",\"hasOutput\":true,\"level\":\"suggestion\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-19T16:20:51.116Z\",\"uuid\":\"4b0f34ee-d79d-4814-a578-063528caedad\",\"toolUseID\":\"a9aeba52-7d78-48fe-bb08-fbd074a5e606\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"4b0f34ee-d79d-4814-a578-063528caedad\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"be7201dc-0742-46dc-83f7-b77432d86dbe\",\"version\":\"2.1.47\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"transient-mapping-sparrow\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"<task-notification>\\n<task-id>a4ec7c5</task-id>\\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01Uep5BsvUozLWW7GK71uSse</tool-use-id>\\n<status>completed</status>\\n<summary>Agent \\\"Security review of changes\\\" completed</summary>\\n<result>I now have a comprehensive view of the changes. Let me compile the full security review.\\n\\n---\\n\\n# Security Review: Replace `filepath.Walk` with `git ls-files --others --exclude-standard`\\n\\n## Executive Summary\\n\\nThe change replaces `filepath.Walk` directory traversal with `git ls-files --others --exclude-standard` for collecting untracked files in two contexts: (1) capturing initial session state, and (2) identifying files to delete during rewind. The change is **low-risk overall** given this is a local CLI tool running inside user-owned git repos. However, there is one finding worth addressing (filenames containing newlines) and several informational observations.\\n\\n**Overall Risk Rating: Low**\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Detailed Findings\\n\\n### Finding 1: Filenames Containing Newlines -- Incorrect Parsing (Medium)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go`, lines 1246-1253\\n\\n**Description:**\\nThe `gitUntrackedFiles()` function splits git output on `\\\\n`:\\n\\n```go\\nfor _, f := range strings.Split(raw, \\\"\\\\n\\\") {\\n    if f != \\\"\\\" && !isProtectedPath(f) {\\n        files = append(files, f)\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nGit filenames can legally contain newline characters. When this happens, `git ls-files` without the `-z` flag will quote such filenames (wrapping them in double quotes and escaping special characters), or the newlines will cause one filename to be split into multiple entries. This leads to incorrect file paths being returned -- phantom entries that do not correspond to real files, or split entries that fail to match any actual file.\\n\\nNotably, the same codebase already handles this correctly in `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/temporary.go` at line 1078, where `git status --porcelain -z` is used with NUL-separated output:\\n\\n```go\\n// Use -z for NUL-separated output (handles quoted filenames with spaces/special chars)\\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \\\"git\\\", \\\"status\\\", \\\"--porcelain\\\", \\\"-z\\\", \\\"-uall\\\")\\n```\\n\\n**Impact:**\\n- A filename containing a literal newline (e.g., created by `touch $'file\\\\nname'`) would be parsed as two separate entries, neither matching a real file.\\n- In the rewind context (`manual_commit_rewind.go` line 355), `filepath.Join(repoRoot, relPath)` would construct an incorrect path. The `os.Remove()` call would fail silently (file not found), so no unintended deletion occurs. However, the real file would not be deleted when it should be.\\n- In the `collectUntrackedFiles` context, the split filename would be stored in `UntrackedFilesAtStart`, causing incorrect preservation decisions during rewind.\\n\\n**Exploitability:** Very low. Requires a user (or agent) to intentionally create a file with a newline in its name. Git discourages this. In practice, nearly no one does this.\\n\\n**Recommendation:**\\nUse the `-z` flag to get NUL-separated output, matching the pattern already used in `checkpoint/temporary.go`:\\n\\n```go\\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), \\\"git\\\", \\\"ls-files\\\", \\\"--others\\\", \\\"--exclude-standard\\\", \\\"-z\\\")\\ncmd.Dir = repoRoot\\noutput, err := cmd.Output()\\nif err != nil {\\n    return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"git ls-files failed: %w\\\", err)\\n}\\n\\nraw := string(output)\\nif raw == \\\"\\\" {\\n    return nil, nil\\n}\\n\\nvar files []string\\nfor _, f := range strings.Split(raw, \\\"\\\\x00\\\") {\\n    if f != \\\"\\\" && !isProtectedPath(f) {\\n        files = append(files, f)\\n    }\\n}\\nreturn files, nil\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 2: No Command Injection Risk (Informational -- No Issue)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go`, line 1239\\n\\n```go\\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), \\\"git\\\", \\\"ls-files\\\", \\\"--others\\\", \\\"--exclude-standard\\\")\\n```\\n\\nThe `exec.CommandContext` call uses only hardcoded string arguments. No user input or variable is interpolated into the command or its arguments. The `cmd.Dir` is set to `repoRoot` which comes from `git rev-parse --show-toplevel`, not from user input. There is no command injection vector here.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 3: Path Traversal in `filepath.Join(repoRoot, relPath)` -- Mitigated (Low)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_rewind.go`, line 355\\n\\n```go\\nabsPath := filepath.Join(repoRoot, relPath)\\nif removeErr := os.Remove(absPath); removeErr == nil {\\n```\\n\\n**Description:**\\nIf `relPath` from `git ls-files` output contained a path traversal component like `../../../etc/passwd`, the `filepath.Join` would resolve it to a path outside the repository, and `os.Remove` could delete an arbitrary file.\\n\\n**Mitigating Factors:**\\n1. `git ls-files --others --exclude-standard` returns paths relative to the repository root. Git does not output paths containing `..` components in its `ls-files` output. The data source is the git index/working tree, not arbitrary user input.\\n2. The `isProtectedPath` check at line 1253 in `common.go` filters `.git/` and `.entire/` paths, but does not check for `..` traversal. However, since the data source is git itself, `..` would never appear.\\n3. The old `filepath.Walk` code had the same trust model -- it walked filesystem paths and deleted files found during traversal.\\n\\n**Recommendation:**\\nAs a defense-in-depth measure, you could add a `..` check to `gitUntrackedFiles()`:\\n\\n```go\\nif f != \\\"\\\" && !isProtectedPath(f) && !strings.Contains(f, \\\"..\\\") {\\n    files = append(files, f)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis is optional given the low risk, but it would guard against any hypothetical git bug or edge case.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 4: `isProtectedPath` Check Is Sufficient After the Switch (Informational -- No Issue)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go`, line 1253\\n\\nThe `isProtectedPath` filter is applied inside `gitUntrackedFiles()` and prevents `.git/`, `.entire/`, and agent config directories from being returned. This protection is applied in the same way as the old `filepath.Walk` code.\\n\\nHowever, there is an important difference: the old `filepath.Walk` code used `filepath.SkipDir` to skip entire protected directory trees efficiently. The new code relies on `git ls-files --exclude-standard` which already excludes `.git/` (git never lists its own internals). The `.entire/` directory would appear in the output only if it is not gitignored. Looking at the `EnsureEntireGitignore` function (line 667), the `.entire/` directory gets its own `.gitignore` but the directory itself is not necessarily in the repo root `.gitignore`. So `.entire/` files that are not covered by `.entire/.gitignore` could potentially appear in the output -- but `isProtectedPath` correctly filters them.\\n\\n**Assessment:** The protection is sufficient. No issue.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 5: Git Binary Unavailability (Low)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go`, lines 1239-1243\\n\\n```go\\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), \\\"git\\\", \\\"ls-files\\\", \\\"--others\\\", \\\"--exclude-standard\\\")\\ncmd.Dir = repoRoot\\noutput, err := cmd.Output()\\nif err != nil {\\n    return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"git ls-files failed: %w\\\", err)\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Description:**\\nIf the `git` binary is not available on PATH, `cmd.Output()` returns an error. This error propagates as:\\n- In `collectUntrackedFiles()`: The error bubbles up. If this fails during session start, untracked files would not be captured, meaning those files could be deleted during a later rewind.\\n- In `Rewind()` (line 333-337): The error is caught as non-fatal and logged to stderr. Rewind proceeds without deleting any untracked files, which is the safe default.\\n\\n**Assessment:** The error handling is appropriate. Rewind gracefully degrades. The only concern is that `collectUntrackedFiles()` failure at session start could lead to data loss during rewind (untracked files present at start not being preserved). However, this is the same behavior as the old code -- if `filepath.Walk` failed, the same issue would occur. And git being unavailable when running a git-integrated CLI tool is an extreme edge case.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 6: `.gitignore` Exclusion Could Skip Security-Relevant Files (Informational -- By Design)\\n\\n**Description:**\\nThe old `filepath.Walk` code collected ALL untracked files (including gitignored ones). The new `git ls-files --others --exclude-standard` excludes files matched by `.gitignore`. This means:\\n- Files in `node_modules/`, `build/`, or other gitignored directories are no longer collected in `UntrackedFilesAtStart`.\\n- During rewind, these files are also not considered for deletion since `gitUntrackedFiles()` does not return them.\\n\\n**Security Implication:**\\nThis is actually a security improvement. The old code would walk through massive directories like `node_modules/`, which is both slow and unnecessary. Gitignored files are not part of the git working state and should not be managed by the checkpoint system. The test `TestShadow_GitignoredFilesPreservedDuringRewind` explicitly validates that gitignored files survive rewind, and `TestShadow_GitignoredFilesExcludedFromSessionState` validates they are excluded from session state.\\n\\n**Assessment:** Correct behavior by design. No issue.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 7: No Timeout on `exec.CommandContext` (Low)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go`, line 1239\\n\\n```go\\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), \\\"git\\\", \\\"ls-files\\\", \\\"--others\\\", \\\"--exclude-standard\\\")\\n```\\n\\n`context.Background()` has no timeout. If `git ls-files` hangs (e.g., due to a network-mounted filesystem or corrupt git index), the CLI would hang indefinitely. The old `filepath.Walk` had the same issue (it could hang on a network mount).\\n\\n**Recommendation:** This is a low-priority, pre-existing pattern. The same `context.Background()` is used throughout the codebase (e.g., `GetWorktreePath`, `GetGitCommonDir`, `DeleteBranchCLI`). If you want to address it, a project-wide effort to add timeouts to git CLI calls would be appropriate, but this is not specific to this change.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Risk Matrix\\n\\n| # | Finding | Severity | Exploitability | Action |\\n|---|---------|----------|----------------|--------|\\n| 1 | Newline-in-filename parsing | **Medium** | Very Low | Fix: use `-z` flag for NUL-separated output |\\n| 2 | No command injection | Informational | N/A | No action needed |\\n| 3 | Path traversal in `filepath.Join` | **Low** | Very Low | Optional defense-in-depth: reject `..` paths |\\n| 4 | `isProtectedPath` sufficiency | Informational | N/A | No action needed |\\n| 5 | Git binary unavailability | **Low** | Very Low | Already handled gracefully |\\n| 6 | `.gitignore` exclusion behavior | Informational | N/A | By design, tested |\\n| 7 | No timeout on exec | **Low** | Very Low | Pre-existing, not specific to this change |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Remediation Roadmap\\n\\n**Priority 1 (Recommended before merge):**\\n- **Finding 1**: Switch `gitUntrackedFiles()` to use `-z` for NUL-separated output. This is a small change that aligns with the existing pattern in `checkpoint/temporary.go` and eliminates the edge case completely.\\n\\n**Priority 2 (Nice to have):**\\n- **Finding 3**: Add a `..` path component check in `gitUntrackedFiles()` as defense-in-depth.\\n\\n**No action required:**\\n- Findings 2, 4, 5, 6, 7 are either informational or already handled correctly.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Security Requirements Checklist (for this change)\\n\\n- [x] All inputs validated and sanitized -- git output is parsed and filtered through `isProtectedPath`\\n- [x] No hardcoded secrets or credentials\\n- [x] Proper authentication on all endpoints -- N/A (local CLI tool)\\n- [x] SQL queries use parameterization -- N/A\\n- [x] XSS protection im